<DOC><DOCNO> AP880520-0296 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 0844EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-SunshineStrike     05-20 0215</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Sunshine Strike,0225</SECOND><HEAD>Tentative Agreement in Silver Mine Strike</HEAD><DATELINE>KELLOGG, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Picketing has ended at the nation'slargest silver mine after a 4{-hour negotiating session producedtentative agreement on a three-year contract.   Negotiators for 260 striking miners and Sunshine Mining Co.announced the agreement late Thursday, the ninth day of the walkout.   The union's negotiating committee will recommend ratificationwhen members of United Steelworkers of America Local 5089 vote onthe offer a week from Saturday, said Steve Brown, unioninternational staff representative.   ``It took a lot of work and two years,'' Brown said.   Workers will return starting with the graveyard shift Sunday,Brown said.   Production work will resume Monday, said Harry Cougher, vicepresident of Sunshine's local operations.   Both sides refused to release details on the settlement untilunion members could review it.   Workers at the Sunshine Mine downed tools and walked out atmidnight May 10 after overwhelmingly rejecting a contract offer.Medical coverage, pay, job classifications and productionincentives were among the unresolved issues.   The mine reopened last November after an 18-month shutdown dueto depressed silver prices. Union members agreed to return undercompany-imposed terms while negotiations continued, then struckwhen the talks broke down.   Negotiations resumed Tuesday, ran well into the night Wednesdayand returned Thursday afternoon.</TEXT></DOC>